			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Will EQ2 Kill EQ before it's ever released?<a name="32411"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 1 04 9:53 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>It's obvious that, Sony wants everyone to buy EQ2.  I mean, no reason they wouldn't want them to.
<br />

<br />
But just how far are they willing to go to achieve that goal? 
<br />

<br />
This latest DX9 change which is almost universally hated leads to a few questions.  This change did 1 obvious thing --- it raised the bar of what it takes to play EQ1.  I'm fairly sure the geometry changes weren't intentional and merely a side effect of this, but the changes to the system requirements are even more so of an issue.  Alot of people who could play EQ before, can't.  Alot of people who could Duel-box on one system before, can't.
<br />

<br />
These people will have to upgrade now, if they want to play the game they've already invested their time into, and, quite frankly, are addicted to.
<br />

<br />
EQ2 is going to require some fairly high system specs.  A good Video Card, ram, etc.  Could it be that, Sony is forcing people to upgrade in order to play EQ1....so that they'll have the neccesary system requirements to play EQ2?
<br />

<br />
Odds are, when EQ2 is released, many of those without the system specs to play it, won't.  Simply not worth it since they've already got EQ1.
<br />

<br />

<br />
So what'dya'll think?  Is this DX9 change just a business ploy, or is there to be some good to come of it?  So far it's introduced nothing but bad.</span></td>
