				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Will EQ2 Kill EQ before it's ever released?<a name="32433"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 2 04 2:20 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>They've stated from the begining that EQ2 is a seperate project and they don't expect it to unseat EQ1.  They do expect that a lot of people will end up playing both games and they're probably right.  Right now I play AC2 and EQ, I'll drop the AC2 account for EQ2 or WoW or Lineage2 depending on which I end up enjoying more. 
<br />

<br />
DX9 isn't universally hated and they did some pretty extensive research into what kinds of systems current players were using to see how well upping the requirements would go over.  Based on the responses to the surveys they put out repeatedly last year, remember those?  And the system info that gets sent to SoE every time you log in, they detirmined something in the neighborhood of 90% or more of current players were capable of running dx9.
<br />

<br />
Other than a few bugs they're still ironing out, I really like the new dx9 support.  Antialiasing is 100% better, animations are smoother and more natural looking, lighting and shading effects are more natural looking as well.  Go up and look closely at the models faces and features, pay closer attention to how shadows fall and how lighting effects play out,  everything looks and runs much better.  Most of the lagginess and other issue, most, not all, are platform issues.  Meaning a bad dx9 install, a corrupted or old driver, some unusual system configuration etc.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
